description.narrative: By 2022 government and partners have institutional capacity to ensure pregnant women, new-borns and adolescent girls, especially from marginalized groups have equitable availability, access, knowledge and demand for quality maternal, new-born and adolescent health care services both in community and health facility, in selected states, which contributes to Early Childhood Development, Hiv Prevention, Maternal And Newborn Health. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

description.narrative: Maternal mortality ratio declined further to 122 per 100,000 in 2017 as compared to 130 per 100,000 for 2015 with a steady decline noted across most UNICEF supported States. 90 of 280 UNICEF supported high delivery load facilities in the aspirational districts achieved the minimum scores required for labour room quality certification. 1,061,197 newborn received care at the SNCUs in 2019; an increase of 28,960 compared to 2018. Newborn mortality at SNCUs further declined to 8.8% in 2019 from 9.7% in 2018. 15 % of ASHAs in UNICEF supported aspirational districts have been trained on HBYC modules. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:13/01/2020
